@Travis Smith look, all I'll say is, there's many things that's reasonable to expect people to cover themselves (such as housing or college) but there's a number of things that are unreasonable to expect people to cover themselves. Healthcare being one (simply due to it's ludicrous expense that results in people dying when they forego care simply due to costs) and transportation being the other (as it is a proven fact access to transportation is the greatest factor in determine how successful a person will be, cited source from Wendover Productions)

 and I can confirm both of these having been poor myself. We cannot afford health insurance for me, so if I get so much as just an accident and break my leg, I'd have to be left for dead on the side of the road, as the medical costs would be too outrageous and the debt would ruin our lives and make us wish to be dead either way. 

And for transportation , I am very lucky right now that I was able to even get a cheap clunker for under $1,500 to get me to work and college, before this, I had nothing, I had no way to get out to college to further my education to increase the amount I'm paid, I would have had no way to travel for job opportunities outside of a couple local convenience stores, which needless to say wouldn't be enough to live off of. If there were a simple bus service here and an Amtrak station put in, I could easily reach the city and have my job opportunities expanded and a way to much college from the existing bus services in the city. But because none of it exists, I'm forced to take the clunker, or remain poor my whole life.﻿

@Travis Smith look dude, let me just say this, I'm not a socialist nor will I ever be, and I do agree that there are people that will cry out for more. However, like I said, there should at least be a minimum provided to allow people a jump-start in life. As you said about employer provided healthcare, what good would that do someone without a way to get to a job without it? And what good would it do for someone who ends up getting a disability that doesn't put them fully out of work but limits them to part time jobs? When you're born into a low income family, you're pretty much going to remain stuck there with no social mobility, can't afford a car to get to higher paid work? Too bad, enjoy barely making ends meet at a local convenience store or McDonalds. 

I do also agree that there are many bad charities that just take the money and run, there's many, maaany out there like that, which is exactly why it's suggested that the government do it. Sure it's not perfect, but it's kept more in check and is often obliged to release financial reports, while a private charity can withhold them to not show their greediness.

For the ACA, I will also agree it's terrible, we've been affected by it too, it pushed health insurance out of the affordable range for us, and now we're stuck paying that extra fine that comes with not having health coverage. It's terrible for people like you, and it was terrible for people like me, it was overall terrible. This is however, exactly why there's calls for true taxpayer paid healthcare with plans such as Medicare for All having been proposed. It cuts out the health insurance deal completely, the hospitals don't change, it just simply becomes taxes pay the bill (and yes, I'd be fine with a tax increase, because there's nothing exactly wrong with higher taxes. In fact most of the rest of the world doesn't even understand the U.S.'s hatred towards taxes, we're taxed pretty low on the world stage, yet people complain it's too much)﻿

